A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.
transformed_texts:
I will study social work to help children who have been hurt or not taken care of, and to support troubled families. Good values I can give to social work are: service, respect, being ethical, and helping others improve their relationships and my skills. These values are important to social workers and to me personally.

In high school and college, I saw people run away from their problems or use things that did not help. Because of this, I studied psychology at Piedmont College. I still did not know what to do after graduation in 2009. One day, I met a sixteen-year-old boy who had run away from his bad parents. I went to his house to help. The police told me to talk to his parents, and I did. They said their son was “bad” for asking for help. I started thinking about social work after this.

Social justice is important in social work. Society says the individual is important, but we want to be like everyone else. I am different and do not want to be like others. I protested against social injustice in school: coloring my hair, wearing different clothes, piercing my ears, and fighting racism and discrimination. I will keep fighting for social justice.

This paper talks about two models that explain sleep disorders, like insomnia. One is the biological model, which looks at genes and health. It studies how genetic information is passed down and how sleep is affected by medical problems. The other is the sociocultural model, which looks at how sleep is affected by our environment, including race, ethnicity, and social status. This review looks at these models and explains how they help us understand insomnia. It also talks about different kinds of sleep disorders, like Dynamismies and Parasomnias. The review then says which parts of this study are good and which are not.

The biological model of sleep disorders looks at genes and physical health. A part of the brain called the hypothalamus helps control sleep and wakefulness. This study used mice to find that a part of the brain called the orexin neuron has a special receptor called the GABAA receptor. When the receptor is active, it helps people sleep. If it's not active, it can cause sleep problems. The study used a drug called baclofen to see if it helps mice sleep more. It did. This shows that mice and humans might be similar in how they sleep. If a person has a problem with the receptor, they might not sleep well. The sociocultural part of this study means that if this receptor is passed down, it could affect sleep. This could make it hard for people to do well in school, work, and other daily tasks.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short definition. Then, it explains how to diagnose it, with examples of problems. Finally, it shows how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) means the brain does not process sounds well. People with CAPD hear normally but have trouble understanding things they hear. Their brain cannot separate words or understand background noise.

The first mention of CAPD was in the 1950s, called "auditory imperception". Italian researchers started testing children with communication problems in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced a test. A meeting in 1977 started more research on CAPD.

People with CAPD have different problems. They may not hear sounds in space, not hear two sounds at once, or not understand speech changes. One sound can block another. They may not understand what they hear or understand the order of sounds.

To diagnose CAPD, doctors use different tests. This may include asking patients to listen and answer questions. No one test works all the time. There is no known cause for CAPD. Tests often give patients sounds and ask them to identify words or numbers. More advanced tests record sounds in the ear.

The play Twelfth Night shows that even though disguise can help hide secrets for a long time, it can also cause big problems. When a person stops hiding, they may feel lonely. They must decide if they should protect themselves or their relationships. Some people will not like being tricked. The topic of changing gender roles is hard. It brings up many questions. Why does someone change their identity? In Viola's case, she changes to protect herself. She tells Olivia: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…" (5.1.247-249) She becomes a man to stay safe. But this makes her feel alone and causes problems with Olivia and Orsino. Olivia thinks Cesario is a man and falls in love with her. Orsino also loves Cesario. This is a bit progressive, but to modern readers, it shows how deception can help people face hidden feelings. Olivia's love for Cesario might be fake because she was interested in a man. But she also falls for Sebastian easily and calls Cesario her sister. It seems she likes people who are pretty.

German colonial rule is known for its harshness. This was true especially in German South West Africa, where many Ovaherero and Nama people were killed. However, the German colonial empire was different in many ways. The education in colonies was also different. In German East Africa, now called Tanzania, the British found many educated Africans after taking over in 1919. The German education in Cameroon and other colonies was also praised. However, in South West Africa, now called Namibia, education was mostly done by missionary groups. The government only helped a little. Many Europeans were educated, but very few Africans were. This was different from other colonies. Many factors caused this difference. This paper will look at these factors. It will pay special attention to new research on what settlers and colonial leaders thought about African natives.
There are many books about education in the German colonial empire. Most are in German and were written in the early 1900s. Some books compare education in different colonies. Some books look at specific parts of education. Cohen's study, for example, compares South West Africa and East Africa. He says the large settler population in South West Africa caused many differences in the education system. South West Africa had a mild climate, but very little rain. This made it less suitable for large farms. So, fewer Europeans moved there. This is why there were fewer settlers in South West Africa than in East Africa.

The popular music genre is now very large. It includes many styles like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk. Each big genre has many small styles within it. Heavy metal rock started 40 years ago. It has become very different and expressive. It shows many feelings, often dark feelings. People quickly found many ways to change and make new styles within heavy metal. Today, there are many kinds of metal music. It's hard to say what heavy metal is now. It started from a place of darkness and drugs. Music like Helter Skelter shows this.

Henri Rousseau started painting only after forty, when he worked as a customs inspector in France. He had no formal art training, but he loved to dream. In his painting "The Dream" (1910), he shows a woman in a dream, amazed by nature. This painting shows Rousseau's dream to be famous and accepted. He wanted to please other artists and art lovers. But he faced a choice: become like others or stay his unique self. He chose to be different. He did not want to be like other artists. He wanted his own style. Even though he began painting late, he kept trying until he was accepted. Matisse, a famous artist, started around the same time as Rousseau. But they were different. Matisse wanted to be unique, while Rousseau wanted to fit in. But Rousseau never gave up. He kept painting what he loved until he was accepted.

Many great thinkers have said that ethics and aesthetics are connected. This means truth and beauty are linked. I believe this is true because we can feel both ethics and aesthetics without learning them. They are like explanations of why something is good or beautiful, not rules to follow.

We cannot fully explain why something is good art or moral. For example, we can talk about the Mona Lisa's background or contrast, but these do not explain why it is good. When people talk about their favorite art or literature, they often say, "There's just something about it." This means there is something more, something we cannot explain.

Ethics and art both have a transcendental nature. This means they cannot be fully explained. As Kant said, "Ethics is transcendental." I believe this transcendental part is what makes art and morality powerful. It is the unseen power that connects them.

We feel both ethics and art deeply. They affect us in a way that we can experience but not fully explain. This is especially true for literature. As McKean said, "Literature's moral quality is what makes it unique." We need values in life, and literature gives us these. This is why literature is important to us.

Germany today is a powerful country with many cultures. These cultures come from the mountains of Munich and the Baltic Sea in Kiel. You can feel this culture from Cologne on the Rhine, through the middle of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden by the Elbe. Germany, as we know it now, comes from many different tribes and sources.

Germania is the old home of the Germans. The name "Germany" comes from the Germanic tribe called Tungrians. This tribe was known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gauls. The name "Germania" may also come from a spear called a "ger," which they used in battle. It might also mean "to shout" in the Old Irish language, showing they were loud or noisy. (Tacitus, 98; Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC; O.E.D, 2010)

The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans in AD 98. He said, "I think the Germans are original and mixed with no other races. In earlier times, people moved to Italy or Germany on ships, not by land. Who would leave Asia or Africa for Germany, with its wild land, bad weather, and serious people?" (Tacitus, 98)

The Romans did not conquer Germania. They sent soldiers to fight there and brought back goods and skills from the Germanic tribes. (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

I looked down, not understanding. The view made my brain think, but I did not connect it to anything. I felt like an artist looking at a picture. The art book I used said to put a square around pictures to make them simple. I could not do this with the bowl of fruit in front of me. I could only look and feel amazed. I felt like a beginning artist in front of famous art.
My hand held the brush. I wanted to create. Water was calm and empty. Pieces of matter broke away and disappeared. My hand hit the toilet handle again. The brown thing did not move. I cleaned the toilet with a mop. I felt strange and tired. My tie was tight. I looked at the toilet. I thought, "I will clean this."

Teenagers are dying in car accidents. Several reasons cause this problem. The National Institutes of Health say the teen brain is not ready for driving. Inexperience also causes bad driving, leading to accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also have more accidents when they drive with friends. A study showed this. California and other states try to make teen drivers safer by giving them temporary licenses. These licenses limit when and how teens can drive. But these licenses are not enough. The youngest drivers are not ready to drive safely. A psychologist says even 18 is too young. USA Today reports that teens under 19-20 often take risks for fun. So, delaying driving until these risks go down makes sense. If we keep giving licenses to young teens, more teens will die in accidents. By 2010, many new teen drivers will be on the road. Schools can teach driver's education, but no one under 18 can drive. They can still get a provisional permit and need practice hours. California requires 6 hours behind the wheel and 50 hours with an adult. A national law would help protect teens. This idea is not new.

I looked at many old Edison films at the Library of Congress. I chose to watch all fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use editing to make illusions. My study focused on the way these films are structured and the change in film techniques over time. At the start of the 20th century, trick films were usually set in a stage-like area, with the camera not moving. They used long and medium shots, not close-ups. This comes from theatre and vaudeville traditions, where people see the whole show at once. In "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors enter and move back and forth, but the camera does not follow them. Most trick films have one main idea, often a magic trick or disappearing act, and are short, about a minute long. However, a trick film can have many physical shots combined to make one illusory shot. For example, in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), the physical shot with Mary's head is combined with other shots to make the film seem like one continuous shot.

John Taylor from Caroline was a very early believer in the Republican Party. He worked as an agriculturalist. This job, plus his short time in politics, made him known for his strong opinions about freedom and government. His beliefs about a good farming system guided many of his views on government. He wanted to keep and support the best careers.

John Taylor thought the United States could create a perfect system because there was no traditional way before it. He believed in the natural rights of people, that they are all connected. He thought the government should not control these rights. He said that the "state of nature" meant strong and evil people controlled, but in a civilization, it should not be this way.

To create this perfect society, Taylor wanted a government that understood good and evil in people. He believed in a dualistic morality. He said that government is run by people, so it has both good and bad traits. He defined good principles as those that protect property, help farming, and stop big business. A good government, he said, would work fairly no matter who runs it. He believed people are driven by self-interest, but this is only bad if it harms others. A good government is needed to keep this evil and watch for bad principles.

Taylor, like other strong Republicans, wanted to follow the Constitution very strictly. He wanted a government with only the powers listed in the Constitution. He thought a big government was expensive and likely to be unfair. However, he also thought a simple, literal reading was dangerous without considering the writers' intent. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true charter of the United States because it describes it as a group of states, not one nation.

Refer to Figure 17. Submission numbers for commuter logs fell sharply in the third month. This was surprising. The reasons for this drop might be many. Winter in New England means fewer people travel by bicycle or on foot. December also ends the fall semester. People are busy with schoolwork and grades. The commuter log might be forgotten. December is also busy with holidays. Students and faculty often take a month-long break. Classes restart in late January. The project started with excitement, but this often decreases. To fix this, we created Carpool Challenge Week in March. This increased log submissions for that month. Another big problem was people liking to drive cars. It is hard to make them change. So, we gave out many prizes. These were gift certificates for local stores and services. It would be interesting to see if bigger prizes, like a nice bicycle or hybrid car, could increase participation. The value of the prizes did not change during the project. If the prizes got bigger over time, people might be more interested. The gift cards worked well at first, but bigger prizes later might have helped.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a type of security that follows an index, a commodity, or a group of assets. It trades like a stock on an exchange. One benefit of ETFs is that they provide diversification, just like index funds. But ETFs also have other advantages. For example, they allow you to sell short, buy on margin, and purchase only one share in a trade. However, there is a downside. You have to pay a commission for each trade, like you would for a stock. ETFs also offer a wide range of funds.

In this study, we will look at the IHF ETF and compare it to its top 10 holdings. We will see if owning one ETF is better than owning a portfolio of the 10 stocks. We will also check if there is a better way to group these stocks.

We will only consider the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Here are these holdings and their percentages.

To compare the ETF and the top 10 holdings, we will calculate the Beta and Return of each. The Beta and Return of the top 10 holdings are shown in the chart below.

From the chart, we see that the return of a portfolio with the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF. The Beta of the top 10 holdings is also 0.12 less than the ETF. This suggests that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings might provide a higher return with a lower risk. However, we cannot be sure if the ETF and the top 10 portfolio are statistically different yet.

To check this, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compare it to the ETF IHF.

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe’s favorite poems. In Dream-Land, he uses the word “Thulé” in lines 6 and 56. This word comes from Virgil. Virgil used it to talk about an island north of Britain. He thought it was the end of the known world. Some people also think Poe got this word from a German writer named Goethe. Goethe wrote a poem called “The King of Thule” in his work Faust. Both Poe and Goethe wrote about a lonely king who lost his wife. In “Dream-Land,” the speaker also feels lonely and sad. This shows that Poe was influenced by Goethe’s work.

Poe used the word “Thulé” twice in his writings. He used it in The Pit and the Pendulum and also in Dream-Land at the beginning and end of the poem. Some people think that “The King of Thule” and “Dream-Land” are like two stories that show each other. The speaker in Dream-Land talks about a dark and lonely land. This is similar to what happens to the king in “The King of Thule.” Poe might have been thinking about this when he wrote Dream-Land.

Poe admired Goethe and his works. He also liked the writer Tennyson. Tennyson might have helped Poe learn about Goethe. People often read and copied Goethe’s works after he first wrote them.

California law: Could a customer injured from slipping on apple sauce in a store be awarded extra money?
A judge will not quickly dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for extra money. She must show the store manager did something bad on purpose.
Palmer can say the manager was bad because he knew many people slipped before, but did not clean the spill. He also did not clean it when told twice.
On October 13, 2009, an employee told the manager, Paul Martin, about the spill. Martin said he was eating dinner and did not have time to clean it.
Later, another employee told him again. Palmer slipped on the spill at 5:30 pm. Five people slipped before in 2009.
Palmer can sue for money. We are thinking about asking the judge to stop her claim for extra money.
A law in California says extra money can be given if a person acted with badness or on purpose. This means the manager must have known the spill was dangerous. He must have known people could slip and hurt themselves.

I took a course on Islam four years ago at CBC. In class, we debated if Islam is a hostile religion. This question is still important today. After 9/11, media views of Islam changed. We couldn't have had a president named Barack Obama with a Muslim background in 2001. The Prophet Muhammad's biography is interesting. It shows Muhammad as a humble martyr, not a conqueror. Many people came to believe in his teachings. There are similar stories about Jesus and Muhammad. Some stories seem made up. They might be trying to make Muhammad seem like Jesus. I think they want to show Muhammad as a good, gentle man. But history shows he was not gentle. I don't think Muslims today know the real history of Muhammad's power.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs changed after his time. This happened in the development of Christian ideas.

In history, we see Christianity moving far from its start. This happens as people learn and think new things. Some people hold onto old ways, but they may not be important. In the future, Christians will want to know what Jesus really taught. This will make a big change in Christianity.

Many people will want to know the true meaning of Jesus' words, not just the words themselves. This will mean many layers of beliefs will disappear. When this happens, Christianity will be more like it was when Jesus lived. The church will be strong, and it will help people gather in one way.

People will see less difference among Christians. Before, there were many differences. Now, people will be more like one another.

History has many changes. For example, Christians were once killed by the Romans. Later, the Roman Empire became Christian. Our country changed from slavery to leadership. A big change will happen in Christianity, too.

So, what happened after Jesus lived? Before, there was only Judaism. It had one God and special books. The Jewish people had many beliefs. Some thought one way, others another.

I think that The Jungle shows how people inside are naturally greedy and selfish. They only care about themselves and making their lives good, not about others. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The owners and managers of big factories only want to make their companies and factories big and good. They do not care about people or animals that get hurt because of their factories. Upton Sinclair shows this in his writing, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". Sinclair shows that the owners do not care about the smoke or the animal waste from the many pens. The owners and managers also do not care about their workers. They force them to work many hours and lay off many people without notice and without help finding a job. In that time, there were few laws or rules to protect workers. Managers and owners could do whatever they wanted. Workers lived and worked in very bad conditions. There were no agencies or unions to help them. The workers were like slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers".

Many writers use different ways to make readers feel a certain way about important subjects. Some techniques are better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he pairs an adjective and a noun that do not usually fit together to create a special feeling around a subject. Other times, he gives meaning to a symbol and uses it again for the same purpose. Fitzgerald uses this technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, like white/gray and red/pink, and then uses that meaning to remind readers of a feeling around an important object.

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show uniformity. White is nicer and higher class, while gray is older and faded. Fitzgerald shows this at the beginning of the novel. Daisy and Jordan are always in white. Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is powdered milky white. The only time people are not wearing white is when Nick sees Gatsby’s party: “the halls... are gaudy with primary colors.” Fitzgerald also uses white and gray to describe common or plain people or places: Jordan and Daisy had a white girlhood together, there are gray cars and gray land in the valley of ashes, the Italian child is gray, and the dog-seller is a gray old man.

After building meaning for white and gray, Fitzgerald uses them to show unimportance or uniformity around certain subjects, starting with Daisy. After a long time without using these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as dressed in white in a little white roadster. Readers start to see Daisy as less important, more like a uniform addition that Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses this technique again around Daisy to show she is less important.

San Diego County is a good place for farming because it is sunny and warm. Many things grow here, like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People buy organic food from farms in this area. The farmers also offer tours and places for hiking and birdwatching. This kind of farming can help the land owner get government money and improve the land for animals.

Organic farming is good for the environment. It helps many plants and animals live. However, it costs more than regular farming. It needs more work to keep the plants healthy without chemicals. This land in Potrero, San Diego County, is 160 acres. It has many trees and plants. Some animals live here that are in danger of disappearing. Native Americans lived here a long time ago. People used to raise cows and cut wood here. The land owner wants to farm this land and help the animals.

I found a farm in the same area that grows organic food. The farm uses government money to help with costs. This farm also helps animals live on the land. The land owner can get money from tours and other activities on the farm.

Culture is important in negotiations. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not simple or the same for all people. Saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are easy" is not true. A negotiator should understand how a culture thinks and acts. This can help in talks. It is not important to judge or change a culture. It is important to respect it. This can help in talks.

Culture is not just about a country. Some companies have their own culture. Some have long work hours. Others are more relaxed. Some companies let employees help charities. Others do not. American companies have different cultures. Some are more relaxed, others are stricter. Some cultures are not as different as they seem.

Understanding the values of a culture is also important. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not make others look bad. If a culture values a hard bargain, a negotiator will not give up easily. Knowing these things can help in talks, but it is also good to learn about the other person. This can make talks better.

"The fool says, 'There is no God.' This idea is from a Bible book called Psalms. It appears in the first part of a problem about God's existence. The author is St. Anselm. He thinks we can find God by believing and thinking. He believes that God is in our minds and we can understand God by thinking about it. St. Aquinas also believes in God. He thinks we can prove God's existence with reason and evidence. He gives five arguments: change, cause, things needing a cause, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Both authors believe in the same God. But neither gives a complete reason to believe in God."

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince became known as Buddha. He left the world, became wise, and taught people about Buddhism. Today, the most common type of Buddhism is called Theravada Buddhism. It is around twenty-five hundred years old. In Sri Lanka, people celebrate the Theravada Water Cutting ceremony. Monks and others take part. This event may not have been taught by Buddha, but it is important in the religion today.

The Theravada Buddhist community has changed over time. This is true for both monks and laypeople. Their beliefs and traditions have changed due to both Buddhist and non-Buddhist influences. These influences can be good or bad.

Buddhism has core beliefs, including the Triple Gem: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is made up of the Tripitaka, which has three parts: Sutta Pitaka, Vinaya Pitaka, and Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has the teachings of Buddha. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for living. The Abhidhamma Pitaka explains Buddhist beliefs.

Buddhists believe in the Four Noble Truths. These truths are: life is suffering, desire causes suffering, suffering can be overcome, and the way to overcome suffering is to follow the Eightfold Path. The Eightfold Path has eight parts, including right understanding, right intention, right speech, and right action.

Buddhists follow different rules. Laypeople have five precepts, which are not to kill, not to lie, not to steal, not to misbehave sexually, and not to take intoxicating substances. Monks follow many more rules.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. This rivalry was like many others between bordering nations. It began with fights about religion, culture, and traditions, but also over land. The high point of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War, which the United States won. Many other fights also happened, but the rivalry ended before World War I. The rivalry was like others because the nations shared a border and had different interests and ideas. David M. Pletcher said, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems." Indeed, both nations are close to the United States and have been rivals. Other Latin American nations have good relations with the United States. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145) Sally Frahm said that Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries, like the United States and Mexico had a Cold War-like rivalry, but over religion instead of politics. This dislike came from the English and Spanish distrust of each other. This made it hard to have good foreign relations. (Frahm 2001 p. 86) Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in this time. Most disputes were about borders and raids. These raids happened until both countries used military force on their borders. (Schmitt 1974 p. 97) Schmitt said the rivalry ended when Mexico became dependent on the United States and American interests changed from taking land to helping Mexico's economy. (Schmitt 1974 p. 109, 110)

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly sick. I did not know I had an illness inside me. I was a nurse at the time. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security. I heard that nurses always have work. I wanted to be a scientist or journalist too, but I chose nursing.

Now, I am disabled and cannot work. I am 46 years old and alone. I have no money. I get money from Social Security Disability. I have nothing left to call my own. Every day is hard and I feel bad about myself. I am not sure about my future.

I am not alone because my family and good friends help me. When big problems happen, we need each other.

There are always emergencies in life. We cannot control everything. No matter how much we prepare, some things are too big to solve alone.

We should not put all our trust in big government. Instead, we should learn to trust each other again. We should help each other and ask for help when we need it.

The people who built this country did not do it alone. They had compassion and shared resources. They worked together, not on their own.

Be ready for emergencies. I have a disaster kit. I have first aid supplies and water purifying tablets. I have plastic sheeting and duct tape for windows. I have flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned food. If you have land and resources, grow your own food. Have a wood stove if you do not live in an apartment.

While you prepare, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules that guide the way they change? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even now, scientists cannot define in math the simplest forms of life. Today, math models are used to study shells. Our study uses math to understand the changes and rules of shell formation in Prunum. We use X-ray images and a program called CerioShell. We make models of shell shapes and combine them with other studies. Shells are tubes that turn around a middle column. The number of turns can be counted. The opening where the animal comes out is called the aperture. Shells can be seen from different sides. We can count the turns and make math models to change the shape of shells.

The rate of neonatal and infant deaths in Indonesia has not changed much in the past ten years. While the country is making good progress on some goals, like water and sanitation, it is not doing well in child and maternal health. There are many reasons for this, and the health system needs to be strengthened rather than just focusing on special programs.

Indonesia has made improvements in births with trained workers, but many births still happen with traditional workers who cannot help with serious problems. There is also a decrease in the number of children under five treated for diarrhea by a doctor. Post-birth care is also not good.

Cesarean rates are still low, with 4% of births. This is lower in rural areas and shows that healthcare is mainly in cities. There is also a big gap in how many rich and poor people use healthcare services.

To improve neonatal and maternal care, the country needs to decide whether to work on special programs or strengthen the overall health system. Special programs can be good, but they can also cause problems if they get too much money and people. They can also duplicate services.

Victorian novels usually focus on the rich people of the time and details. Two books, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and strange things. This makes the characters and their feelings clearer. Both books use dreams or dream-like states to do this.

In Oliver Twist, strange things happen in Oliver's mind. When he is shot, he feels pain and fear. He does not understand what is happening. He feels like he has no control over his life. He does not try to save himself. This shows that he feels defeated. It is as if Fagin has broken him.

In Wuthering Heights, time seems to pass fast and slow. The day goes quickly, but the night lasts forever. It is always silent and dark.

I worked in an after school program helping young students. I was good at English and reading. One boy, Adrian, had trouble reading. He had perfect English, but he didn't know the English alphabet. His mother spoke only Spanish. When I met her, I found out Adrian's problem. He could read, but he didn't know letters. I hope he is better now.

I tell this story to show the language barrier in schools, especially in California. Even students who speak perfect English may have reading problems. Adrian's problem was easy to solve. We just taught him the alphabet and how to read. But for students who barely speak English, the solution is harder. There is no one answer. We need a mix of things: dual language, mainstream immersion, tutors, ESL classes. We can't just do one thing.

First, the dual language system is good. It helps all children, not just those whose first language is Spanish. Children in these programs do better in school. But not everyone thinks this is a good idea. They fear it wastes resources. But it's not true. If we make this the rule in schools, all children will learn more. How do we do it? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have special helpers who know both languages.

From childhood, many of us believe in something bigger than ourselves. Some go to church or temple. Some look inside themselves. Many follow what their parents believe. But some reject it. Yet, we all seek our own way to understand spirituality. We try to find a light in darkness. My father's favorite bird was a cardinal. One night, we sat on our porch, listening to rain. He was thin, hair thin. He stared into the rain, lost in thought. I felt alone and afraid. I hugged him and sat close. He passed that December, before my birthday. In the night, I felt angry and alone. I did not want to see him die. So, I did not watch. I did not want to remember him like that. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is an "Old-New" mix. Ian Watt calls it this in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have many thoughts about Gothic. Some think it is good, some think it is bad. The original Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto, uses old ideas and new ideas to make a new kind of story. Walpole uses old theater parts and new nature mimicry in his story. The Gothic genre has medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. In the time of The Castle of Otranto, "gothic" meant many things. It was seen as old or simple. The mix of old Gothic and new novels makes Gothic last. It becomes old and new to readers today.

Many Gothic novels have chivalry. Chivalry is the training of knights. It is important in Gothic because of what knights represent—brave, honorable, good. Gothic writers use this idea to show how society has changed. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a troubled time. He thought the good in people from the Gothic era was lost in today's society. He shows this in his characters, like Frederic. Frederic is a prince and has suffered. He is brave and honorable. This is like a chivalric knight. However, it is also like a Gothic trope of excess.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from order to customer. The term was created in 1982 by a consultant named Keith Oliver. He described managing the process of planning, doing, and controlling supply chain activities to meet customer needs quickly and well. The process has six parts: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to offer good customer service.

Production is the first step. It is the start of the supply chain. It decides when, why, where, and how things are made. Managers look at the market to understand what customers want. They then decide which products to make and how many. They also choose the best place and plant for production, considering customer needs and satisfaction. After this, they focus on scheduling and equipment maintenance.

Supply is about making important decisions to choose the best processes and partners. A company might have many divisions for a single product. Each division has different equipment and workers. Managers must choose the best fit for each process. They may also decide to work with other companies. Outsourcing can create speed, which is the ability to make quality things quickly while keeping costs low.

Hitler is alive in Burma. A sign says this.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a piece of cardboard. The message is written in Sharpie. Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. Its name is Myanmar. The government is very bad. People cannot do what they want. Only the military is in control. In 2007, many people protested. They were monks. They wore yellow robes. This is called the Saffron Revolution. Many people died. A Japanese photographer was killed. Many people are still dead. Colonel Hla Win said many people were killed. The government does not want people to protest. This is not new. Many governments do not like people to protest. Early Roman emperors thought they were gods. They controlled all things. Japanese leaders are called gods. They make cell phones. They also make hara-kiri. President George W. Bush talks to Ted Haggard each week. He is the leader of Stupid People Worldwide. Some famous examples are the Tiananmen Square protest in 1989. Many people died there. The Rwandan genocide in the 1990s was a bad event. Many people were killed. Hitler's Third Reich was also bad. Many Jews were killed.

Duke Ellington's music is special because he played for a long time and was good at creating music for his band. He played piano quietly in many songs, but he wrote good music for his band members. He helped each player show their special skills. He also wrote songs with many instruments playing together. Ellington wrote songs that were new and beautiful. He used the sound of his band members to make their music better. For example, in a song called "Creole Love Call," he used a voice as an instrument. He made a song with a slow, smooth sound at the beginning, and then added a rough sound. He also made a song with a trumpet and a voice together. In another song, "Hot and Bothered," he used a trumpet and scat singing together. In "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," he used a trombone to start the song. All these songs show how Ellington used different instruments and sounds to make his music special.

She wanted something, but she did not know what it was. This feeling started when she was 14. She was a teenage girl, just beginning her teenage life. It was still there three years later, when she was 17. Now, she wanted a person, not a thing. But she did not like any boys. Boys tried to talk to her, but she did not like any of them. She did not know why. She thought about this for a long time, but she still did not know why it happened. So, she lived her life, always questioning her desires.

Every day at home was usually calm. Her parents were calm and did not argue. They did not argue with her either. The only thing they argued about was her being independent and having a fun personality. She was a nice person, and people liked her because of this.

Today, though, was not a calm day. She walked around the house, looking for new ideas. Then, she heard a scream from the kitchen. She ran there to see her mother on the floor. She asked, "Mom? Mom, what happened?" Her mother said, "Ow. I need you to take me to the hospital." Her daughter helped her mother and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital had a smell like disinfectant and sickness. But she did not think about this because she was worried about her mother. She carried her mother to the doctors. They took her mother to be looked at. Her daughter waited and worried.

Her mother fell off a stepping stool while trying to get a vase from a high cabinet.

This study shows that following the Mediterranean diet (Med diet), as shown by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," helps reduce the risk of heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet is similar to the Med diet but with more plant foods and lower animal products. Moderate alcohol is allowed.

Previous studies showed that the Med diet is good for reducing the risk of death from heart disease and stroke. This study is new because it looks at the risk of stroke and stroke death.

The study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years old, without heart disease or diabetes. They were nurses in the Nurses' Health Study in 11 US states. The study asked about their diet six times from 1984 to 2004. More than 95% of nurses stayed in the study for 20 years. The study also asked about exercise, smoking, and other health habits. Reports of heart disease, stroke, and death were checked.

Scientists used a special math method (Cox proportional-hazard modeling) to find how the aMed diet score affected the risk of heart disease and stroke. They found that women who followed the diet well had lower risk of heart disease and stroke. During the 20 years, 2391 heart disease cases, 1763 stroke cases, and 1077 deaths from heart disease and stroke were found. Women who followed the diet best had the lowest risk.

In 2007, America had a big financial problem. People lost their jobs, the housing market fell, and big companies went broke. This is called a recession, and it is still going on. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it.

The crisis was caused by poor and careless decisions from politicians. They told banks to give loans to people who were not good at paying back. This was called sub-prime loans. These loans were added to a weak and young financial system. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also helped with these loans by buying and selling them.

The problem started in 1999 during the Clinton era. The president wanted to stay in power. To do this, he made it easier to get loans. In 1999, Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned about this. He said Fannie Mae could have problems in a bad economy. But the problems came anyway.

Many things made the crisis worse. New kinds of loans were used. These were called adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s). These made the economy depend more on the housing market. When the housing market fell, many people and banks lost money.

In 2007, five big U.S. banks had $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts. This was 30% of America's economy. Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply. Lehman Brothers stopped. Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to become banks with strict rules. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were put under government control in 2008.

The crisis made people lose faith in banks and the financial system. It also showed how important it is to have strong rules and regulations to prevent such problems in the future.

Exposition is not helpful. It's when you tell us things that happen before the main story. You need to show us these things instead of telling us. This makes the story more interesting. If you tell us about a character's past, show us how it affects their present. If you tell us how characters feel, show us through their actions and words. If you tell us about a place, show us the details that make it unique. Showing is better than telling because it engages readers and lets them experience the story themselves.

For example, instead of telling us about a character's past, show us how their past makes them behave now. If a character used to be in the Air Force, show us how they act because of that. If they are the night manager of a gas station, show us how they handle their job. If they have a dream of owning the gas station, show us how they work towards that dream. If they had Eggs Benedict for breakfast, show us how that moment fits into their day. By showing these things, we understand the character better and care about them more.

So, when you write, remember to show, not tell. It makes your story more engaging and satisfying.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was live on NBC 4 in the morning of August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife. Her name was not mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his picture and he looked very bad. They talked about it for about two minutes. They said he stabbed her many times and was arrested. I thought that was enough time for this story.
The second story was about a shooting of a boy named Travis Buyers. He was 18 years old and was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was very badly hurt, but no one was arrested. The SWAT team was looking for the person who did it. This story was short. I think this might be because he was a black person or from a black neighborhood. I have seen this before. When a white person is a victim of a crime, the media talks about it a lot. But if a minority person is a victim, it might not even be mentioned.
The next story was about a bullet hole in a helicopter. They talked about where it might have happened. They said it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. They said it was not clear who did it. Crime-Stoppers offered a five-thousand dollar reward for information.
Next, they talked about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon. They said the temperature would be mid to low eighties for the weekend. They wanted to keep people watching by saying it was a preview.
They also talked about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF. They said the person who did it was a dark-skinned black man. They described him as tall and thin. They talked a lot about how dark he was and what he looked like.
Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin from Texas. He was arrested for sending marijuana to Ohio. They said he was sentenced to 300 months in prison. It was not clear why they said that instead of just saying 25 years. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but that did not seem important to the story.

Brothers have a special connection. It is strong and cannot be broken. This bond has many feelings. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. They see themselves in their brother. In difficult times, the bond shows the true feelings. When these feelings are clear, they have a big cost. Understanding the feelings of this bond means dealing with the results. When brothers look at each other, they see their true selves, not how others see them. Their actions and the results of those actions show their true character.

In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers explore this theme and the strong feelings that go with it. They go on a long journey in a beautiful place. Sadness and pride meet in the end. Only one brother survives. The story shows the feelings of the main character, Doodle, and his brother. The narrator's view also shows their feelings and how they influence their actions.

The main character's actions are mainly about pride. He wants a brother he can teach. He wants someone to play with and share secrets. But Doodle is not like other children. He has a weak heart and cannot do what the main character wants. The main character feels sad and angry. He even thinks about killing Doodle once. But when Doodle smiles at him, the main character feels love. This shows that his bad feelings are not very strong. In his heart, he loves his brother.

The brain is a complex way to process information. Technology has changed how we understand it. At first, it was compared to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now a computer. These comparisons can be useful, but they can also cause mistakes. The brain gets information from the senses. It turns touch, heat, sound, and light into electrical signals. These signals are changed by the brain's codes in two ways: from the bottom up (putting together small details) and from the top down (using past decisions). When you look at a black box on white paper, bottom-up processing helps you see the box. Top-down processing helps you know it's a black box, not a hole. The brain decides what is important. It stores information in different ways: short-term (for 20 seconds) and long-term. Information is stored differently based on what kind of sense it comes from. The brain has many ways to organize information, like a computer program or a map of concepts.

Aldous Huxley criticizes future technology and the capitalistic system in "Brave New World." People in this society love their community very much, and they want to be happy all the time. They are controlled by the World Controller. Huxley uses ideas from Marxism to show problems with this system. One such idea is homogeny, where people are very similar. The system makes people believe they are happy and free, but it is not real. This is called false consciousness. The common people do not know how bad the system is. They want to buy and spend as much as they can. They do not know they are controlled. The upper classes know the system is bad, but they do not change it. In Brave New World, people do not have real feelings or relationships. They talk about people only for their looks. They do not care about other people's feelings. They only care about their own happiness and their place in society. They are like the proletariat in Marxism, who are tricked into thinking they are superior. They do not know they are controlled. They do not care about other people. They only care about being happy and following the system.

I live at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Moving around campus is hard. In my first year, I lived in East Halls, farthest from the center. Walking to classes like those in Willard building took 25 minutes or more. An old student told me, East Halls was once separate by unused land. Now, this space is filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As campus grows, moving around becomes harder. What is the best solution? Biking is good, but students need to use them, and campus must be for them.

My friend who bikes now said, “Bikes are best. They are the only way to get around.” Biking is healthy and quick. One bowl of oatmeal and a little exercise can travel 30 miles. I live off-campus, like many students. Buying a bike was the smartest decision. It takes 5 minutes to ride to Thomas building, 25 minutes to walk. Without a bike, walking would take 30-40 minutes each way, 2.5 hours weekly. That’s too much time.
